00:01:29.155 --> 00:01:30.735
Uh, so, uh, the office chose

41
00:01:30.735 --> 00:01:32.495
to look at child poverty for a range of reasons.

42
00:01:33.115 --> 00:01:35.135
Uh, you know, firstly, there's general agreement

43
00:01:35.165 --> 00:01:37.015
that addressing child poverty is important

44
00:01:37.035 --> 00:01:38.695
to improving the lives of New Zealand children

45
00:01:38.795 --> 00:01:40.255
and their families, um,

46
00:01:40.255 --> 00:01:42.455
but also a range of social outcomes in the longer term.

47
00:01:43.235 --> 00:01:45.255
Uh, experiencing poverty as a child is linked

48
00:01:45.255 --> 00:01:48.495
to inequities in school achievement, adult employment,

49
00:01:48.595 --> 00:01:51.255
income levels, and behavioral health and cognitive outcomes.

50
00:01:51.795 --> 00:01:54.295
So, uh, reducing child poverty is in the public interest.

51
00:01:55.415 --> 00:01:57.715
Uh, secondly, uh, child poverty has multiple

52
00:01:57.715 --> 00:01:58.875
and complex causes.

53
00:01:59.255 --> 00:02:02.155
Uh, there are many public organizations that are responsible

54
00:02:02.155 --> 00:02:05.115
for responding to it, and there's no simple solutions.

55
00:02:05.495 --> 00:02:08.155
So the need for coordinated government action

56
00:02:08.215 --> 00:02:10.275
to address the issues, it, it was pretty clear.

57
00:02:10.775 --> 00:02:13.115
And our office has a continuing interest in

58
00:02:13.115 --> 00:02:15.835
how well government agencies work together to address, uh,

59
00:02:15.895 --> 00:02:17.315
our most complex challenges.

60
00:02:17.775 --> 00:02:19.515
And we've done work, uh, like this in the past

61
00:02:19.515 --> 00:02:21.955
before we've done work looking at, um, you know,

62
00:02:21.955 --> 00:02:23.155
the cross government response

63
00:02:23.155 --> 00:02:24.475
to family violence and sexual violence.

64
00:02:24.855 --> 00:02:27.475
And we've looked at, um, how well the system meets the, uh,

65
00:02:27.475 --> 00:02:29.635
mental health needs of Young New Zealanders as well.

66
00:02:30.975 --> 00:02:34.275
And lastly, uh, the Children's Act 2014 requires the

67
00:02:34.275 --> 00:02:36.195
government to have a strategy to reduce child poverty

68
00:02:36.255 --> 00:02:39.075
and to mitigate the impacts of socioeconomic disadvantage.

69
00:02:39.695 --> 00:02:41.435
And the Child Poverty Reduction Act, uh,

70
00:02:41.435 --> 00:02:42.835
2018 sets out measures

71
00:02:42.835 --> 00:02:45.595
and requires ministers to set targets for reducing poverty.

72
00:02:46.135 --> 00:02:47.355
And we also know that, um,

73
00:02:47.355 --> 00:02:48.835
government agencies are engaged in a range

74
00:02:48.835 --> 00:02:50.395
of activities designed to make a difference.

75
00:02:50.575 --> 00:02:52.475
So we wanted to see how those arrangements

76
00:02:52.475 --> 00:02:53.595
were working in practice.

77
00:02:54.095 --> 00:02:55.475
Uh, so that's what I'm gonna say.

78
00:02:55.475 --> 00:02:57.275
I'll hand over to Sarah now, who will talk a bit more,

79
00:02:57.495 --> 00:02:58.675
um, about what we did in

80
00:02:58.775 --> 00:03:00.125
The key findings of our work.

81
00:03:06.165 --> 00:03:10.425
Greetings to the committee. What we looked at was

82
00:03:11.045 --> 00:03:13.825
the effectiveness of the arrangements in place

83
00:03:13.965 --> 00:03:15.105
to reduce child poverty.

84
00:03:15.485 --> 00:03:18.585
So specifically, we looked at the governance management

85
00:03:18.925 --> 00:03:20.825
and monitoring and reporting arrangements,

86
00:03:21.785 --> 00:03:24.445
and our focus was on the four public organizations

87
00:03:24.555 --> 00:03:26.725
that at the time have oversight

88
00:03:26.825 --> 00:03:28.365
of the child Poverty work program.

89
00:03:28.985 --> 00:03:30.445
So that's DPMC,

90
00:03:30.445 --> 00:03:35.045
or was D-P-M-C-M-S-D, statistics, New Zealand and Treasury.

91
00:03:36.615 --> 00:03:38.435
In terms of what we found,

92
00:03:38.965 --> 00:03:42.235
there are some important foundations in place.

93
00:03:42.925 --> 00:03:45.875
Successive governments have been clear on what they want

94
00:03:45.875 --> 00:03:47.755
to achieve, um, and on their roles

95
00:03:47.775 --> 00:03:51.475
and responsibilities, we found that the monitoring

96
00:03:51.495 --> 00:03:54.355
and reporting on child poverty is done well.

97
00:03:54.535 --> 00:03:58.155
So that was a strength. There's regular reporting on defined

98
00:03:58.405 --> 00:04:00.835
child poverty measures, and public

99
00:04:00.975 --> 00:04:03.035
and non-government organizations value

100
00:04:03.255 --> 00:04:04.675
and use that information.

101
00:04:06.555 --> 00:04:10.285
What wasn't clear is how child poverty initiatives

102
00:04:10.425 --> 00:04:13.645
to reduce material hardship should be sequenced

103
00:04:13.865 --> 00:04:15.525
or coordinated with each other

104
00:04:16.465 --> 00:04:18.525
or with relevant frontline services.

105
00:04:19.145 --> 00:04:21.125
And we know that that's a particular issue

106
00:04:21.125 --> 00:04:24.125
because integrated frontline services are especially

107
00:04:24.125 --> 00:04:25.325
important to meet the needs

108
00:04:25.325 --> 00:04:28.525
of our most disadvantaged people experiencing multiple

109
00:04:28.525 --> 00:04:30.005
socioeconomic disadvantages.

110
00:04:30.825 --> 00:04:33.685
But what we heard is that it's difficult

111
00:04:33.745 --> 00:04:36.325
for many public organizations, uh,

112
00:04:36.345 --> 00:04:39.205
to work in a joined up way, um, with each other

113
00:04:39.585 --> 00:04:42.045
and with community services at the front line.

114
00:04:43.685 --> 00:04:47.865
So we've recommended that MSD needs to give more focus

115
00:04:48.005 --> 00:04:50.305
to addressing that issue of coordination,

116
00:04:51.205 --> 00:04:53.745
and in our view, a more detailed

117
00:04:54.385 --> 00:04:57.945
